<h3>Step 3: Apply the Formula</h3>
<p>Let us use a realistic example. A plumbing company spends $500 per month on automated SEO tools and content. After 6 months, they attribute $18,000 in new customer revenue to organic search.</p>
<ul>
<li>Total SEO cost: $500 x 6 months = $3,000</li>
<li>Revenue from SEO: $18,000</li>
<li>ROI: ($18,000 - $3,000) / $3,000 x 100 = 500%</li>
</ul>
<p>This is conservative. Many local businesses see higher returns, especially in high-ticket service industries.</p>
<h3>Step 4: Account for Customer Lifetime Value</h3>
<p>The basic formula measures first-transaction revenue. But local businesses thrive on repeat customers. A plumber who fixes a leak this month might replace a water heater next year. Factor in lifetime value for a more accurate picture.</p>
<p>If the average plumbing customer spends $800 on the first job and $2,400 over three years, the true ROI of acquiring that customer through SEO is much higher than the initial transaction suggests.</p>
<h3>Step 5: Measure Over Time</h3>
<p>Local SEO ROI compounds. Month 1 might show a loss. Month 3 might break even. Month 6 typically shows strong positive returns. Month 12 and beyond is where the real gains materialize. Track ROI quarterly, not weekly, to account for the natural ramp-up period.</p>
